    "bloodline": {
      "name": "Descendant of the Wendigo",
      "description": "In the colonial nights of the far north, across moonlit plains where those few brave souls built their outposts, the legend of the Wendigo haunted their campfires: a creature of ice and hunger, an avatar of deprivation given claws and fangs, an embodiment of famine and cold. Such was the name given to one of the first Nosferatu to journey to the New World: a feral, monstrous thing, perhaps even a wight, it nevertheless Embraced at least one other to ensure its ravenous Blood survived the ages.\n\nWinter and hunger were its kin. Cold could not touch the Wendigo, and death by freezing did not close a meal. The Blood remembered the taste of bodies found stiff in the snow, the last thin pulse of starvation in the veins. It learned to sustain life without relieving deprivation. It learned to skinwalk, slipping into the hides of winter predators, moving as wolf or owl.\n\nYou descend from this creature of myth. Hunger and winter are your playthings, as well: You endure them both, and you make everyone else endure them, too.",
      "merits": [
        {
          "name": "Curse of the Wendigo",
          "value": 1,
          "description": "The cold and the hungry will do anything, agree to anything, to live another day.",
          "rules": "Your Blood gains the ability to sustain mortals in place of food and heat. However, this does not satiate their hunger or comfort them with warmth, it merely keeps them alive. Such mortals continue to suffer the effects of starvation or hypothermia, up to but not including the point of incapacitation.\n\nGain a +2 bonus to Intimidation or Persuasion rolls when exploiting the effects of this deprivation in another.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Veins of Winter",
          "value": 2,
          "description": "The Wendigo is a creature of winter as much as hunger, and your Blood carries this affinity.",
          "rules": "You are immune to the effects of cold temperatures.\n\nAdditionally, you may feed from the frozen corpses of mortals that perished from starvation or hypothermia as if they were still alive (but you cannot reduce your Hunger to 0 by feeding on that which is already dead). Such blood is always intensely ischemic and never carries a dyscrasia.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Skinwalker",
          "value": 3,
          "description": "You share the Wendigo's ability to skinwalk.",
          "rules": "Gain Protean as an in-clan Discipline. You must choose a winter predator when given the choice of an animal form.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Father of Monsters",
          "value": 4,
          "description": "Whether or not the Wendigo truly was a wight, you have inherited Blood tainted with a corrupting power, which spreads to your ghouls.",
          "rules": "Any ghouls that you have purchased as Retainers gain an additional Discipline dot from among those you have learned, and increase their tier by one level: RETAINER ●: Average, RETAINER ●●: Gifted, RETAINER ●●●: Deadly. If you have a famulus, your famulus' tier increases to Gifted. This power warps your ghouls physically, afflicting each with the Repulsive Flaw as they grow both gaunt and monstrous.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Feast or Famine",
          "value": 5,
          "description": "Hunger both drives and sustains you, as it did the Wendigo of legend.",
          "rules": "You gain the ability to sense the hunger and cravings of other Kindred. You know when any Kindred you can see is at Hunger 4 or above or under the effect of a Compulsion.\n\nWhile fully sated at Hunger 0, your monstrous appearance relaxes into something more human: While still hideous, your appearance alone will not risk breaching the Masquerade if seen by mortals. Additionally, if you would take a Stain for any reason, you may instead increase your Hunger by one. Finally, your ability to sense hunger in others extends to knowing when another Kindred is fully sated at Hunger 0.\n\nWhile starving at Hunger 5, treat your Blood Potency as one higher for all purposes. Whenever you would make a Rouse Check for any reason, make an additional Rouse Check and choose which roll to keep. Finally, you retain control during hunger frenzy and do not need to spend Willpower to act. Instead, you gain a Compulsion to feed: All actions that are not dedicated to slaking your thirst suffer a -2 penalty for the duration of the frenzy. All other mechanics of hunger frenzy still apply.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        }
      ]
    },
    "loresheet": {
      "name": "The Whisper-Weaver",
      "description": "Kindred speak of Toronto as a city that's lost its leaders, those respected elders who heeded the call of the Beckoning, abandoning their havens and their schemes to fight a war in the east on behalf of sleeping gods. Drake's names come up as examples: the Vault, the Oubliette, and especially the Whisper-Weaver; the mysterious bogeyman in black silks who haunted the Court long before anyone ever heard of Fort York. He's gone, they say, just like Steele, like Bellanger, like so many others who once gave Toronto its sense of strength and stability.\n\nBut you? You know better. Drake may have left the city above, but he only went as far as the city below. For Toronto isn't one city, but two: the Toronto everyone sees above ground, and the Toronto beneath, a world of memories frozen in two hundred years of strata.\n\nDown here, there are storm tunnels older than any zoning law and gaps in foundations that were built before Canada was a country. Hidden corridors, closed-off basements, abandoned subway stations and derelict utility pathways weave through this undercity. Down here, Toronto's oldest sovereign still sits his throne, unknown and unrecognized by every Kindred in the city above, save a very precious few.\n\nYou have earned Drake's trust, enough that he calls upon you, places you in important roles, and challenges you. Where other elders trade in Blood, secrets are his currency. He's careful and deliberate with every piece of information he shares. If you're searching for answers, he might reveal them, but not without a cost, and always in a way that draws you deeper into his complex web. And if there ever comes a night when Drake asks you which move he should make in the city's shadowy game, you'll know it means the story of his “leaving” has finally become more useful as a weapon than as a disguise.",
      "merits": [
        {
          "name": "The Shadow Speaks",
          "value": 1,
          "description": "You are fortunate enough to be among the few people Drake trusts.",
          "rules": "In addition to being aware that the Nosferatu elder remains in Toronto, once per story, you may meet with Drake in a secluded location of his choice. There, he'll reveal what he knows about one secret you're after.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "The Labyrinth",
          "value": 2,
          "description": "Drake's knowledge of Toronto's hidden paths is unparalleled.",
          "rules": "Once per story, Drake will reveal a secret hard-to-detect vantage point from which you can spy on someone. Beyond that, you're on your own: make a loud noise or otherwise reveal your presence and your perfect camouflage loses its use.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Forgotten Friends",
          "value": 3,
          "description": "Drake always favoured outcasts, easily overlooked and easily dismissed.",
          "rules": "They're the people that go unnoticed, like janitors, sanitation workers, or food workers. Once per story, Drake can hook you up with someone who can get you inside, or get you the info you need from the inside, for a price. The individual counts as Retainers (••) for the session, but reverts to Contacts (•) if you spend Experience to make the Background permanent.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": true
        },
        {
          "name": "Whisper-Weaving",
          "value": 4,
          "description": "You have gained your own talents at gathering secrets.",
          "rules": "When you purchase this Merit, gain free Skill Specialties in Investigation (Espionage) and Insight (Secrets). Once per story, you can gain three pieces of secret information through your personal surveillance or close bonds with your network of spies.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        },
        {
          "name": "Phantom's Proxy",
          "value": 5,
          "description": "Drake trusts you more than anyone else.",
          "rules": "When you purchase this Merit, gain Mawla: Drake (•••). Additionally, once per story, Drake will ask your advice on what action he should take to influence Toronto's politics, and take it to make permanent change in the city.",
          "notes": "",
          "purchased": false
        }
      ]
    },
    "timeline": [
      {
        "era": "Pre-Embrace",
        "startYear": 1769,
        "endYear": 1786,
        "affiliation": "nil",
        "details": "- Had lots of \"spare\" siblings, but more survived than expected, leaving their small patch of land unable to feed 6–8 growing young men and women.\n- \"Third brother had a flair for whittling; father sold three of our five cows to get him an apprenticeship as a carpenter\"; he gave away heirloom jewelry to provide dowries for two sisters.\n- By the time it got to Fomórach, there wasn't much left to support him; he'd have to go on his own.\n- Decided to become an indentured servant so he could get a plot of land in the New World, \"the golden land\".\n- Arrived in the New World circa 1785, to a terribly mismanaged colony that was obvious to him even before he arrived, on the boat.\n- Realized that everyone was a Puritan, which made him uncomfortable given he was a Catholic.\n- Drake was attracted to him as a source of information, something he became very good at: getting into earshot of important people, and feeding Drake information.\n- Drake ghouled him early, but he was able to keep functioning while starving even as others suffered. Drake saw his ability to gather information while under intense stress; his \"resting dumb face\" combined with covert intelligence made it easy for others to forget he was there and listening; and he was one of the few who were ghouled with the taint of permanent starvation who didn't abandon his mental faculties.\n- After taking him to another colony further north and seeing him repeat that talent for ingratiating himself and gleaning intel despite suffering, Drake concluded he was something special.\n- After Drake escaped a werewolf encounter, he began to see the value of another pair of eyes, and the fragility of his lineage as the only childe of the Wendigo. He needed to ensure his blood survived the ages.",
        "locations": ["Belfast, Ireland", "East Coast Colonies"]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Lineage",
        "startYear": 1786,
        "endYear": 1838,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "Following the collapse of his new home, Fomórach traveled the colonies with Drake learning the ins and outs of vampirism. Hunted by puritans in the summer and haunted by hunger in winter (and werewolves all year 'round), he learned what it truly meant to be a Descendant of the Wendigo.",
        "locations": ["East Coast Colonies", "Fort York, Canada"]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Violence",
        "startYear": 1838,
        "endYear": 1841,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "Newly released by his sire, Fomórach traveled by boat back to the land of his ancestors. He hoped to find his family, to lend them the fruits of his struggles: life eternal and freedom from hunger were within his ability to grant, even if the cost would be high. Instead, he found his ancestral home raped and pillaged by the British. Enraged beyond measure, Fomórach left for London and proceeded to cut a bloody swath through the neighborhoods of the perpetrators of the Famine. It was only by the mercy of the London Nosferatu Primogen that he survived, and even then he was delivered back to Toronto staked in a coffin.",
        "locations": ["London, England"]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Legacy",
        "startYear": 1841,
        "endYear": 1948,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "After his episode in London, it took Drake time to trust Fomórach with responsibility again. Long decades were spent making him understand the risks he took and the favors he burned with his reckless actions. Drake did not take kindly to being forced to reveal Fomórach's bloodline, and needed time to not totally extinct. Fomórach did not want that; he knew then that at the time of course, intrigue. Fomórach delved deeper into the mystery of his bloodline and took steps to ensure it would not be so threatened again. Traveling to the Ukraine, he took advantage of the Holodomor to seek out a candidate with the fortitude enough not to totally accept the nature of the blood. The vampire is a beast of hunger after all, and the Wendigo is even more so. Mara was well-suited to the blood, too well suited, and Fomórach watched history repeat itself in his childe as she rejected the order and safety of the Camarilla to pursue her own personal crusade which continues to this day. His other childe, sired during the founding of Israel and the resulting Palestinian diaspora (known as the Nakba), remained loyal though his choices in other areas remains questionable.",
        "locations": ["London, England", "Toronto, Canada", "Ukraine", "Palestine/Israel"]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Adversity",
        "startYear": 1958,
        "endYear": 1984,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "The Camarilla runs on tradition, but favors are a close second. It was a favor, long ago, that bolstered the growth of Toronto as a bastion of kindred society in the 1850s and now 100 years later it has been called in. Transmitted through the blood like the curse of vampirism itself, it passed from sire to childe. Oliver Gagnon called for aid on behalf of his childe Lucien, and the childe of Drake answered. Picking up Lucien from the Mojave desert turned out to be the easy part. Driving back up to Toronto together...\n\nWell.\n\nLets just say it was an exciting five years and leave it at that.\n\n(The details surrounding Fomórach and Lucien's time on the road are intentionally left vague for now; they will be explored in more detail during play in a Memoriam sequence.)",
        "locations": ["On the Road, USA", "Toronto, Canada"]
      },
      {
        "era": "A Time of Dominion",
        "startYear": 1999,
        "endYear": 2025,
        "affiliation": "camarilla",
        "details": "Like many elders facing The Beckoning, Drake was forced to face his impermanence. Not mortality, because he had no intention of dying, but to be forced to leave one's unlife's work is hardly a pleasant thing. With this in mind, Drake began to train Fomórach into a suitable successor. No more was he merely a trusted liegbreaker and solver of problems, now he must be made ready to handle the rigors of Camarilla politics. Fomórach was involved in the process of rulership far earlier than most would expect, participating in the primogen council's meeting from behind his sire's veil for years before said sire's \"beckoning\" in 2022, when Fomórach took his place as Nosferatu Primogen and *de facto* leader of Clan Nosferatu in Toronto.\n\nDrake, however, was never Beckoned, and remains hidden in the dark places beneath the city, his continued presence known to very few.",
        "locations": ["Toronto, Canada"]
      }
    ]
  }
}